bWHDnqHxWyIgs4YSHRzTdR1V4CEtF2_LDqAD_i25vzkvtz5aXlWKE4fbPjri\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Assessing the dynamic report line**\\n\\nI’m wondering if the dynamic report line isn't actually `Class.forName(\\\"javax.servlet.jsp.tagext.JspTag\\\")` when using `findAncestor`. It seems that might just be a helper function rather than the main class I'm expecting. It’s a bit confusing to figure out what each part is really doing. I’ll need to dig deeper to clarify this and ensure I’m on the right path!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering metadata collection**\\n\\nI’m pondering whether the metadata collection only applies to the test method. It feels uncertain because static initialization might not be included during the discovery phase. That doesn’t seem ideal. Should I consider creating a field initializer for the test? Hmm, that might not work either, especially if the previous test file isn’t getting tracked and therefore isn't within the workflow. It's definitely something I need to clarify.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating file outputs and structure**\\n\\nI noticed that `git diff` showed no output for the new file since it was untracked, but external tools can still see it. I’m wondering if the workflow tests just the current worktree and not untracked files. Perhaps the test fails due to the public visibility requirement for top-level test classes. I might need to refine the structure to use nested classes instead. Also, it seems I should avoid using `$` in file/class names to prevent complications with naming conventions.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining test class structure**\\n\\nI see there's no issue with \\\"all top-level test classes public,\\\" but there’s a one-to-one mapping between report classes and generated test files. Top-level helpers in the same file could count as extra classes, so I might need to reconsider that. Using static nested classes seems disallowed beca